</div>
<p>Auroras take place when charged particles from the sun, known as the <a class="hawk-link-parsed" href="https://www.space.com/22215-solar-wind.html" data-component-tracked="1">solar wind</a>, flow along the magnetic field lines of Earth and interact with our atmosphere. As the particles are <a class="hawk-link-parsed" href="https://www.space.com/15139-northern-lights-auroras-earth-facts-sdcmp.html" data-component-tracked="1">deflected by the magnetic field</a> to our planet&#8217;s poles, their interactions with the atmosphere dumps in energy and causes the atmosphere to glow.</p>
